            <div type="apparatus" resp="#martaf">
                <listApp>
                    <app><note>Text based on photographs</note></app>
                    <app loc="line 1"><note>Ferrara, Franz (from Müller), Kaibel read [Φ]οῖβον</note></app>
                    <app loc="lines 3-4"><note>After ση--- and after κόσμον, Ferrara read a Κ. After κόσμον the upper end of a vertical stroke can be observed (I, K, H). Franz: ση--- | κόσμον [φιλῇ εἶναι] (after ἱδρυσάμην the name of the dedicant follows: e.g. Σή[μων Ξενίου]); Kaibel Epigr. Gr.: Σή[μων], κόσμον [ἐμῇ] πατρ[ίδι]; Kaibel IG: σηκ[ῷ τ’ ἐπὶ] | κόσμον κ[αλὸν ἔθηκα]; Korhonen: σηκ[ῷ τ’ ἐπὶ] κόσμον <unclear>κ</unclear>[αλὸν ἔθηκα?]. Another possibility can be σηκ[ῷ τ’ ἐπὶ] κόσμον <unclear>κ</unclear>[αλὸν ἔτευξα?]</note></app>
                    <app loc="line 5"><note>Franz, Kaibel Epigr. Gr.: πατρ[ίδι]; Kaibel IG, Korhonen: πατρ--- (name of the dedicant). The traces after πατρ--- suggest Β, Γ, Ε, Ι, Κ, Μ, Ν, Π.</note></app>
                    <app loc="line 5"><note>Korhonen assumed other lines missing after line 5</note></app>
                </listApp>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en" resp="#martaf">
                <p>I raised (a statue of) long-haired Phoebus, far-shooting Apollo, in a sacred enclosure, and added a beautiful decoration. Patr---.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="it" resp="#martaf">
                <p>Ho innalzato (una statua di) Febo dai lunghi capelli, lungisaettante Apollo, in un recinto sacro, e ho aggiunto una bella decorazione. Patr---.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary" resp="#martaf">
                <p>The epigram probably accompanied a statue of Apollo. It consisted of two hexameters (Kaibel’s interpretation in Epigr. Gr. of an elegiac distichon is to be rejected), after which the name of the dedicant in prose should follow (<foreign xml:lang="grc">Πατρ</foreign>---). The epigram has epic echoes, such as the formula <foreign xml:lang="grc">Φοῖβον ἀκερσεκόμην</foreign> at l. 1 (cf. e.g. Hom. Il. 20.39, Hymn.Ap. 134) and the formula <foreign xml:lang="grc">ἑκατηβόλον Ἀπόλλωνα</foreign> at l. 2 (cf. e.g. Hom. Il. 1.370, 5.444, 16.711, 17.333): especially the first formula recurs in the variant <foreign xml:lang="grc">Φοίβῳ ἀκειρεκόμῃ</foreign> in other dedicatory epigrams on stone, cf. IG 4/2, 1 no.433 (= Epigr.ded. 212 Cougny) from Epidaurus (4th CE) and IGUR I no.102b (= Epigr.ded. 247 Cougny) from Rome (2nd-3rd CE).</p> 
                <p>The inscription is dated palaeographically to the 3rd-4th cent. CE (Manganaro’s dating to the Hellenistic age is to be rejected) and comes probably from Catania, even if the provenance is doubtful, since it was found in a group of inscriptions, of which at least one comes from Syracuse (IG 14, no.58 = <ref target="http://sicily.classics.ox.ac.uk/inscription/ISic000875">ISic000875</ref>).</p>
            </div>
